AGI - No other bronchospasm and above all no increase in white blood cells that suggests the absence, at the moment, of infections>. A comforting picture emerges, although in the complexity of the situation, reading the medical bulletin issued every evening by the Vatican on the health of Pope Francis.
&nbsp;
Its clinical conditions "have remained stable">, the prognosis is still reserved. And rightly, doctors keep being careful. It still takes 24 hours to evaluate the effects of yesterday's isolated crisis of bronchospasm, and to exclude an involvement of other organs, for example the kidneys, in addition to the same lungs.
&nbsp;
But the positive news is there. The Pontiff "is apiretic", i.e. he has no fever and "does not show leukocytosis">, i.e. in blood analysis an abnormal increase of white blood cells is not shown. Usually leukocytosis is symptom of infections. As for oxygen, other positive data, in which an improvement can be read, is the alternation between the "long periods of oxygen therapy" to the "non-invasive mechanical ventilation", i.e. a mask covering nose and mouth. And the "good response to gaseous exchanges" was maintained. The Pope also regularly performs respiratory physiotherapy "actively collaborating" and as we still read, "the hemodynamic parameters have always been stable", i.e. the information on the cardiovascular system, therefore blood pressure, blood flow, cardiac function and consequently pulmonary situation.
&nbsp;
His power seems to have not changed. Vatican sources confirm that Bergoglio, "always vigile and oriented", can eat solid and is not fed via flebo. In the afternoon he received the Eucharist, and spent about 20 minutes in prayer in the hat near his room. The mood continues to be good. The working activity today has been reduced even if a new appointment has arrived from the Gemelli and the Pope continues to make his decisions. Among these, the choice to spread tomorrow only the text of the Angelus, as happened in the two previous Sundays.<br> So a more serene day than today. This morning the press room had announced that the night was spent quietly. The crises, then confirmed Vatican sources, had not been presented again and this morning the Pope took a coffee.
